Government Spokesperson, Oumar Guèye, said on Thursday all was done to avoid an explosion in prices of essential staples and other products. If the government has set up a price support scheme for wheat and abandoned some of the import taxes, many Senegalese were still forced to shrink their grocery bills. At the end of a cabinet meeting, the government announced its latest lever to support more than 540 000 low-income households. All are listed on the national single registry and will receive approximately $64 million to cope with the rising cost of living. This new safety net will be launched on May 10. The West African country is grappling with the consequences of global inflation and the disruption of international trade due to the Ukraine-Russia conflict. --AfricaNews--